<p class="display-6"><small>The creative</small></p>
<dl class="row">
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end">The Art Scene</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9"></dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end fw-light fst-italic">pixel, raster, vga, ansi, bbs art, ascii</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9">
        Art scene creations are a form of digital artworks drawn or painted using purpose made software.
        The common forms of this expression are pixel art, ray-tracing art, monochrome text or 'ascii' art, and colored text 'ansi' art.
    </dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end">The Music Scene</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9"></dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end fw-light fst-italic">chiptune, mod, streamer, tracker</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9">
        Songs of the Music Scene are music tracks composed using purpose made home computer software, 
        often <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tracker_(music_software)">tracker software</a>,
        to create <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chiptune">chiptune</a> or other genres of electronic music. 
        In the early era of 8-bit and 16-bit microcomputers, these songs were often used to demonstrate the audio capabilities of the computer platform.
    </dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end">The Demoscene</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9"></dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end fw-light fst-italic">intros, demos, games</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9">
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demoscene">Demoscene</a> participants combine the art scenes, the music scenes, and 
        their own programming trickery to create visually appealing, non-interactive software demonstrations. 
        Created to demonstrate the graphic and audio capabilities of the chosen computer platform and the technical
        programming skills of the creators. Nowadays, the Demoscene is more focused on art style and design.
    </dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end">The Emulation Scene</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9"></dd>
    <dt class="col-sm-3 text-end fw-light fst-italic">emulators</dt>
    <dd class="col-sm-9">
        Emulation software mimics hardware or operating systems to allow the running of software designed for a different platform. 
        For example, a Windows PC can use emulation software to run games created for the Commodore 64. 
        Emulator software has existed since the earliest days of computing, but the Emulation Scene probably came about in the early 1990s. 
        With hardware hackers who experimented with getting defunct video game console software to play on personal computers.
    </dd>
</dl>
